%header
  .header-content
    .container
    .row
      .col-lg-6.col-lg-offset-3.text-center
        =partial "animated-logo.svg"
        :css
          #pwlogo {
            fill: rgba(255,255,255,0.6) !important;
            transform: scale(1);
            transition: all 1s;
          }
          #pwlogo:hover {
            fill: #fff !important;
            transform: scale(1.1);
          }
          #konamiglow {
            transform: scale(0);
            animation-name: konami;
            animation-delay: 1000ms;
            animation-duration: 12s;
            animation-iteration-count: infinite;
            animation-direction: normal;
            animation-timing-function: ease-out;
            animation-fill-mode: forwards;
          }

          @keyframes konami {
            0% {transform: scale(1);}
            50% { transform: scale(20); }
            100% { transform: scale(1); }
          }
          
    .header-content-inner
      %h1
        = current_page.data.description
      %hr
        %p PipeWire makes it possible to share multimedia processing pipelines between applications.
        %a.btn.btn-primary.btn-xl.page-scroll{:href => "#about"} Find Out More
  =partial "pcb.svg"
        
%section#about.bg-primary
  .container
    .row
      .col-lg-12.text-center
        =partial "workflow.svg"

        %p.text-faded 
          Capture and playback of audio and video with minimal latency
        %p.text-faded 
          Real-time Multimedia processing on audio and video
        %p.text-faded 
          Multiprocess architecture to let applications share multimedia content
        %p.text-faded 
          Support Sandboxed applications. See 
          = link_to "Flatpak", "http://flatpak.org" 
          for more info.
        %p &nbsp;

%section#getting
  .container
    .row
      .col-lg-10.col-lg-offset-1
        %h1.section-heading.text-center Getting PipeWire
        %hr.primary
        %p
          Pipewire is available on 
          = succeed "." do
            = link_to "github", "https://github.com/PipeWire/pipewire"
          To clone the repository, just

        :preserve
          <pre>
            <span class="unselectable">$ </span>git clone https://github.com/PipeWire/pipewire.git
          </pre>

        %h2 Setup
        %p
          Building pipewire is fairly straightforward.
        
        
        :preserve
          <pre>
            <span class="unselectable">$ </span>./autogen.sh --prefix=$PREFIX
            <span class="unselectable">$ </span>make
            <span class="unselectable">$ </span>make install
          </pre>
        
        The 
        %code $PREFIX
        is commonly set to 
        %code /usr
        or
        %code /usr/local

%section#documentation
  .container
    .row
      .col-lg-10.col-lg-offset-1
        %h1.section-heading.text-center Documentation
        %hr.primary
        %p
          A collection of useful pages can be found on the 
          =link_to "PipeWire wiki", "https://github.com/PipeWire/pipewire/wiki"
        %p
          Developers can check out the 
          =link_to "PipeWire API", "https://pipewire.github.io/pipewire/build/doc/html/index.html"
          documentation.

%section#get-involved
  .container
    .row
      .col-lg-10.col-lg-offset-1
        %h1.section-heading.text-center Get Involved
        %hr.primary
        %p
          PipeWire is Free Software and is developed in the open. To get in touch, use the 
          =link_to "pipewire mailing list", "http://fixme.com"
          or 
          %em #pipewire
          IRC channel on Freenode. Code can be found on
          =link_to "Github", "https://github.com/PipeWire/pipewire"
          (along with a 
          = succeed ")" do
            = link_to "wiki", "https://wiki.gnome.org/Projects/pipewire"
          and issues are tracked on 
          = succeed "." do
            = link_to "Github Issues", "https://github.com/PipeWire/pipewire/issues"
